WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:04.890 --> 00:00:07.010
DON HARRISON: Hi, and
welcome, everyone.

00:00:07.010 --> 00:00:09.110
My name is Don Harrison.

00:00:09.110 --> 00:00:12.852
I am pleased to welcome
two authors in front of us

00:00:12.852 --> 00:00:15.310
who are here to discuss their
book, "The Fourth Revolution,

00:00:15.310 --> 00:00:19.190
The Global Race to
Reinvent the State."

00:00:19.190 --> 00:00:22.150
On my far right is
John Micklethwait,

00:00:22.150 --> 00:00:27.860
who is currently the editor
in chief of "The Economist."

00:00:27.860 --> 00:00:31.960
Which one of you, in their
19th year, 20th year,

00:00:31.960 --> 00:00:34.841
took a road trip across
the-- that was you?

00:00:34.841 --> 00:00:36.132
JOHN MICKLETHWAIT: That was me.

00:00:36.132 --> 00:00:37.180
DON HARRISON: That was you?

00:00:37.180 --> 00:00:39.721
So I just wanted to highlight
that that was an important road

00:00:39.721 --> 00:00:42.160
trip, which had a formative
sauna at the end of it,

00:00:42.160 --> 00:00:43.720
with Milton Friedman.

00:00:43.720 --> 00:00:46.170
Did that lay the ground
work for this book?

00:00:46.170 --> 00:00:47.670
JOHN MICKLETHWAIT:
I should explain.

00:00:47.670 --> 00:00:52.440
When I was aged 18 in
Britain, you take a gap year

00:00:52.440 --> 00:00:54.990
before you go on to university.

00:00:54.990 --> 00:01:00.180
And I came to California,
possibly quite a long time

00:01:00.180 --> 00:01:05.420
before many of you here
were born, in 1980.

00:01:05.420 --> 00:01:08.297
And I went to go and stay
with-- I was traveling around

00:01:08.297 --> 00:01:10.880
with a friend, and I went to go
and stay with a cousin of his.

00:01:10.880 --> 00:01:13.130
An elderly man called Antony.

00:01:13.130 --> 00:01:16.970
And we stayed in his apartment
block in San Francisco.

00:01:16.970 --> 00:01:19.180
And he persuaded
us to go and have

00:01:19.180 --> 00:01:22.420
a sauna around the
corner with his neighbor,

00:01:22.420 --> 00:01:23.964
a man called Milton.

00:01:23.964 --> 00:01:26.700
And I sat there,
and Milton asked me

00:01:26.700 --> 00:01:28.490
what I knew about
Margaret Thatcher.

00:01:28.490 --> 00:01:30.800
Neither me nor my friend
really knew much about it.

00:01:30.800 --> 00:01:33.590
And he kept on saying how
the world would change,

00:01:33.590 --> 00:01:37.060
that British Rail
would be privatized,

00:01:37.060 --> 00:01:39.380
that British Leyland,
this old car company,

00:01:39.380 --> 00:01:41.800
would be broken up.

00:01:41.800 --> 00:01:44.142
Margaret Thatcher would
introduce education vouchers.

00:01:44.142 --> 00:01:45.600
That's something
called Monetarism.

00:01:45.600 --> 00:01:48.670
And I was age 18,
19 at the time.

00:01:48.670 --> 00:01:50.940
And I thought this man
was basically on drugs.

00:01:50.940 --> 00:01:53.450
And I looked at
him, and I thought,

00:01:53.450 --> 00:01:54.550
this is completely weird.

00:01:54.550 --> 00:01:56.883
I've just come from Yorkshire,
part of Northern England,

00:01:56.883 --> 00:02:00.790
and we had lessons by candle
light because of the miners

00:02:00.790 --> 00:02:02.100
being on strike.

00:02:02.100 --> 00:02:04.270
And later that week,
I went to go and watch

00:02:04.270 --> 00:02:07.206
The Grateful Dead
play in San Francisco.

00:02:07.206 --> 00:02:08.789
ADRIAN WOOLDRIDGE:
That's a rock band.

00:02:08.789 --> 00:02:10.288
JOHN MICKLETHWAIT:
Nothing, nothing,

00:02:10.288 --> 00:02:13.786
nothing that I saw
then seemed half

00:02:13.786 --> 00:02:18.390
as hallucinogenic than what
I had heard in the sauna.

00:02:18.390 --> 00:02:20.655
And yet, that was
Milton Friedman,

00:02:20.655 --> 00:02:23.120
to my somewhat junior self.

00:02:23.120 --> 00:02:26.560
And actually, in some ways,
it's a nice way into this book.

00:02:26.560 --> 00:02:30.120
Because this book is an
attempt to say to people,

00:02:30.120 --> 00:02:34.300
you may think that
government will never change.

00:02:34.300 --> 00:02:37.345
But it can change very,
very dramatically.

00:02:37.345 --> 00:02:39.630
And in fact, in terms
of the revolutions

00:02:39.630 --> 00:02:41.880
we talk about in Western
government, what's

00:02:41.880 --> 00:02:44.190
interesting about the
Milton Friedman revolution,

00:02:44.190 --> 00:02:46.720
is we say the revolution of
Thatcher and Ronald Reagan

00:02:46.720 --> 00:02:48.380
wasn't really a whole one.

00:02:48.380 --> 00:02:50.480
It was just a half revolution.

00:02:50.480 --> 00:02:51.870
And what we argue,
is that if you

00:02:51.870 --> 00:02:54.395
think that you
should be despondent,

00:02:54.395 --> 00:02:56.770
and you can see lots of people
who are going to troop off

00:02:56.770 --> 00:03:01.350
to the mid-term
elections in November,

00:03:01.350 --> 00:03:02.950
and if you think
of all the people

00:03:02.950 --> 00:03:05.980
who are going off to
vote in Europe this week,

00:03:05.980 --> 00:03:08.740
there's a sort of
despondent apathy there.

00:03:08.740 --> 00:03:12.320
And what we argue in this book,
is that is completely wrong.

00:03:12.320 --> 00:03:14.170
Is that all the
evidence of history

00:03:14.170 --> 00:03:18.090
is that government will
change dramatically when it

00:03:18.090 --> 00:03:19.080
needs to do so.

00:03:19.080 --> 00:03:21.520
And the West has been through
three huge revolutions

00:03:21.520 --> 00:03:22.250
like this.

00:03:22.250 --> 00:03:24.130
But also, very
much to your world,

00:03:24.130 --> 00:03:26.440
is that technology
changes things.

00:03:26.440 --> 00:03:28.220
If all of you, and I
find this incredible

00:03:28.220 --> 00:03:29.845
that anyone at Google
could think this,

00:03:29.845 --> 00:03:32.110
but we do get this
reaction sometimes,

00:03:32.110 --> 00:03:34.720
people tend to think that--
they seem to somehow assume

00:03:34.720 --> 00:03:38.050
that all this change that has
happened to the private sector,

00:03:38.050 --> 00:03:40.172
somehow won't happen
to the public sector.

00:03:40.172 --> 00:03:43.180
And we argue that is
exactly the opposite.

00:03:43.180 --> 00:03:45.500
Every huge revolution
government has been through,

00:03:45.500 --> 00:03:47.445
technology has been
right to the core.

00:03:47.445 --> 00:03:50.102
So that was a long way
segue from your sauna,

00:03:50.102 --> 00:03:51.700
but that is the
message of this book.

00:03:51.700 --> 00:03:53.950
That change is
coming to government

00:03:53.950 --> 00:03:56.780
in a much, much bigger way
than people have thought,

00:03:56.780 --> 00:03:57.880
but with one twist.

00:03:57.880 --> 00:04:02.680
And that is that this time, you
are in competition with China.

00:04:02.680 --> 00:04:03.615
And with Asia.

00:04:03.615 --> 00:04:05.910
And with other places which
are working much harder

00:04:05.910 --> 00:04:07.797
on government than the West is.

00:04:07.797 --> 00:04:08.630
DON HARRISON: Great.

00:04:08.630 --> 00:04:10.974
Well, I do appreciate that
you dove right in there.

00:04:10.974 --> 00:04:12.840
At Google, we always like to
sort of dive right in too,

00:04:12.840 --> 00:04:14.620
and sometimes throw
the PowerPoint away.

00:04:14.620 --> 00:04:17.100
So I'll punch through the rest
of the introduction quickly,

00:04:17.100 --> 00:04:19.360
and then we'll get on with it.

00:04:19.360 --> 00:04:21.510
But I'd note that you
studied history at Oxford.

00:04:21.510 --> 00:04:23.350
You had a productive
career as a banker.

00:04:23.350 --> 00:04:25.620
That is close to my heart.

00:04:25.620 --> 00:04:29.522
But then, unfortunately
became a journalist in 1987.

00:04:29.522 --> 00:04:31.730
You were named Editor's
Editor of the British Society

00:04:31.730 --> 00:04:34.330
of Magazine Editors in 2010.

00:04:34.330 --> 00:04:37.950
And I assume both of you
guys are Friends of Google?

00:04:37.950 --> 00:04:40.630
I've seen a picture in the book.

00:04:40.630 --> 00:04:45.480
And notes that seemed
friendly in the text.

00:04:45.480 --> 00:04:48.623
And on my immediate
right, Adrian Wooldridge,

00:04:48.623 --> 00:04:50.850
who is the management
editor for "The Economist"

00:04:50.850 --> 00:04:52.710
at writes the Schumpeter column.

00:04:52.710 --> 00:04:54.000
Pronunciation OK?

00:04:54.000 --> 00:04:55.290
Good.

00:04:55.290 --> 00:04:57.917
And he was based in DC, where
you were Washington Bureau

00:04:57.917 --> 00:04:59.059
Chief.

00:04:59.059 --> 00:05:01.350
So let me-- I mean, you jumped
in and sort of explained

00:05:01.350 --> 00:05:02.930
the basis of the book.

00:05:02.930 --> 00:05:05.350
I want to say that my
impression of your book,

00:05:05.350 --> 00:05:07.920
or what really stuck to
me, was a certain-- was

00:05:07.920 --> 00:05:12.040
the call to action
that you describe.

00:05:12.040 --> 00:05:14.179
You offer ideas, you
offer a clear roadmap.

00:05:14.179 --> 00:05:15.720
But what I sort of
found interesting,

00:05:15.720 --> 00:05:19.109
is both the history, but
also the clear engagement

00:05:19.109 --> 00:05:19.650
you outlined.

00:05:19.650 --> 00:05:24.221
You know, Mill, Webb,
Cromwell, Richelieu, Gladstone.

00:05:24.221 --> 00:05:28.430
You know, all engaged, all
with a sense of mission.

00:05:28.430 --> 00:05:30.590
We do have this apathy
towards democracy.

00:05:30.590 --> 00:05:33.150
But you try to make us not
just despair about that.

00:05:33.150 --> 00:05:36.290
And to provide examples
of how we move forward.

00:05:36.290 --> 00:05:39.365
Was this-- you know, you
have a roadmap of action,

00:05:39.365 --> 00:05:41.550
and then you also
have a call to action?

00:05:41.550 --> 00:05:42.740
Are both part of the book?

00:05:42.740 --> 00:05:44.530
Or is one more important
than the other?

00:05:44.530 --> 00:05:45.946
ADRIAN WOOLDRIDGE:
Can I start off

00:05:45.946 --> 00:05:48.200
by saying what the
revolutions were,

00:05:48.200 --> 00:05:49.810
just to give people
a sense of why

00:05:49.810 --> 00:05:51.667
we're saying that
there were revolutions.

00:05:51.667 --> 00:05:53.500
Because we tend to
think, we can quite often

00:05:53.500 --> 00:05:56.070
think that the State is
just something that's there.

00:05:56.070 --> 00:05:57.474
Something that we can ignore.

00:05:57.474 --> 00:05:59.140
And what we argue
very much in the book,

00:05:59.140 --> 00:06:04.090
is that the State, has
for the past 500 years,

00:06:04.090 --> 00:06:06.520
been a key to the
competitiveness

00:06:06.520 --> 00:06:08.640
and the best of
success of the West,

00:06:08.640 --> 00:06:10.390
and that the State has
constantly evolved.

00:06:10.390 --> 00:06:13.000
And it's because it's
evolved that the West has

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:14.410
managed to stay ahead.

00:06:14.410 --> 00:06:18.390
If you go back to
the year 1500, you

00:06:18.390 --> 00:06:21.450
would find that
everybody in the world,

00:06:21.450 --> 00:06:23.270
who wasn't completely
deranged, would

00:06:23.270 --> 00:06:26.380
have thought that the future
of the world belonged to China.

00:06:26.380 --> 00:06:29.120
China was much more
dynamic, it was much bigger,

00:06:29.120 --> 00:06:33.220
it was a much more concentrated
civilization than Europe was.

00:06:33.220 --> 00:06:36.220
China-- Europe had
three cities which

00:06:36.220 --> 00:06:39.360
had more than 300,000
people as inhabitants.

00:06:39.360 --> 00:06:42.705
The Heavenly City
in Peking alone,

00:06:42.705 --> 00:06:46.840
had inhabitants of 300,000
people, many of whom

00:06:46.840 --> 00:06:49.650
were civil servants
who were selected

00:06:49.650 --> 00:06:51.700
by objective examinations.

00:06:51.700 --> 00:06:53.910
The most sophisticated
examinations the world

00:06:53.910 --> 00:06:58.110
had ever seen, from the
whole of the Empire,

00:06:58.110 --> 00:07:00.120
to administer this great Empire.

00:07:00.120 --> 00:07:02.990
So, Europe, by contrast,
looks like a sort

00:07:02.990 --> 00:07:05.368
of blood-soaked battlefield.

00:07:05.368 --> 00:07:06.700
A backwater.

00:07:06.700 --> 00:07:08.830
Where you're constantly
fighting over religion,

00:07:08.830 --> 00:07:11.180
you're constantly being
bullied by nobles,

00:07:11.180 --> 00:07:13.710
who all have their
own private armies,

00:07:13.710 --> 00:07:17.732
and are wandering around
in a rather lawless way.

00:07:17.732 --> 00:07:19.670
And the way that
Europe gets ahead,

00:07:19.670 --> 00:07:22.720
is first of all inventing, and
then reinventing the State.

00:07:22.720 --> 00:07:26.060
The first thing Europe does is
invent the State as a security

00:07:26.060 --> 00:07:28.210
State to provide public order.

00:07:28.210 --> 00:07:30.340
That's the fundamental
thing that the State should

00:07:30.340 --> 00:07:32.530
do, to have a public
order revolution, whereby

00:07:32.530 --> 00:07:34.940
the nobles are
brought under control,

00:07:34.940 --> 00:07:37.650
religion is brought under
the control of the State,

00:07:37.650 --> 00:07:41.120
so you don't have any
dissent over religion.

00:07:41.120 --> 00:07:43.470
So, public order,
but the same time,

00:07:43.470 --> 00:07:46.490
a certain measure of
competition between all these

00:07:46.490 --> 00:07:48.444
rather coherent Nation States.

00:07:48.444 --> 00:07:49.860
They're competing
with each other.

00:07:49.860 --> 00:07:53.670
In China, their system is so
big, the Empire is so big,

00:07:53.670 --> 00:07:55.030
that it's very introverted.

00:07:55.030 --> 00:07:56.340
It's very inward-looking.

00:07:56.340 --> 00:07:58.440
When the Chinese
invented gunpowder,

00:07:58.440 --> 00:08:00.300
they used it to
create fireworks.

00:08:00.300 --> 00:08:01.950
Probably a nice thing to do.

00:08:01.950 --> 00:08:06.160
We in Europe use it
to create weapons,

00:08:06.160 --> 00:08:07.730
so to blow people
out of the water.

00:08:07.730 --> 00:08:11.445
When the Chinese were confronted
with the possibility of trade

00:08:11.445 --> 00:08:14.800
with the rest of the world, the
emperor in the mid 17th century

00:08:14.800 --> 00:08:16.550
says, actually,
to all the people

00:08:16.550 --> 00:08:18.529
who are on the coast,
the southern coast, which

00:08:18.529 --> 00:08:20.320
is the most prosperous
part of the country.

00:08:20.320 --> 00:08:21.300
You must move inland.

00:08:21.300 --> 00:08:23.090
You mustn't mix
with those people.

00:08:23.090 --> 00:08:25.020
It's an introverted
Middle Kingdom.

00:08:25.020 --> 00:08:26.590
Europeans, on the
other hand, trade

00:08:26.590 --> 00:08:29.740
with the rest of the world,
conquer the rest of the world,

00:08:29.740 --> 00:08:32.059
create a dynamic, and rather
imperialist, obviously,

00:08:32.059 --> 00:08:33.880
imperialistic civilization.

00:08:33.880 --> 00:08:36.830
So Europe pulls ahead,
because of this invention

00:08:36.830 --> 00:08:39.000
of the competitive
Nation States.

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:42.600
Then in the 18th
and 19th centuries,

00:08:42.600 --> 00:08:44.640
you have a sort of
liberal revolution,

00:08:44.640 --> 00:08:48.560
whereby you have a liberal
State, created as accountable,

00:08:48.560 --> 00:08:51.860
that's efficient, and
that's much smaller.

00:08:51.860 --> 00:08:54.286
So you have a contraction
in the size of the State.

00:08:54.286 --> 00:08:55.660
Because the State
goes from being

00:08:55.660 --> 00:08:58.920
a rate-seeking organization,
which basically deals

00:08:58.920 --> 00:09:01.920
in sinecures, office
sinecures, to employees,

00:09:01.920 --> 00:09:03.640
employs them for
doing nothing at all.

00:09:03.640 --> 00:09:06.510
To saying, actually, we'll
select civil servants on merit.

00:09:06.510 --> 00:09:08.780
We'll solve problems.

00:09:08.780 --> 00:09:12.650
We will create a prison
system, a police system,

00:09:12.650 --> 00:09:16.240
solve the basic problems of
an industrializing society.

00:09:16.240 --> 00:09:17.930
So that's the
liberal revolution.

00:09:17.930 --> 00:09:21.060
And then, in the
early 20th century,

00:09:21.060 --> 00:09:22.900
because people begin
to complain that this

00:09:22.900 --> 00:09:25.169
is a rather hard hearted
vision of the state.

00:09:25.169 --> 00:09:26.960
They begin to complain
that the State needs

00:09:26.960 --> 00:09:29.600
to do more to encourage
economic dynamism.

00:09:29.600 --> 00:09:32.560
You get an expansion of
the role of the State.

00:09:32.560 --> 00:09:34.450
Starting small,
starting with the notion

00:09:34.450 --> 00:09:37.070
that the state should
provide a guaranteed

00:09:37.070 --> 00:09:39.050
minimum of civilized life.

00:09:39.050 --> 00:09:41.690
Education, welfare,
retirement payments.

00:09:41.690 --> 00:09:43.900
But then the ambition
for the State

00:09:43.900 --> 00:09:45.630
gets bigger and
bigger and bigger.

00:09:45.630 --> 00:09:48.550
So, the Labor Party
in Britain, in 1945,

00:09:48.550 --> 00:09:51.570
talks about building
a new Jerusalem.

00:09:51.570 --> 00:09:53.790
Today's absolutely
the anniversary,

00:09:53.790 --> 00:09:56.240
the 50th anniversary of Lyndon
Johnson's great society.

00:09:56.240 --> 00:09:59.050
When he said, we must
create a great society,

00:09:59.050 --> 00:10:02.050
and use the State get rid of
racism, get rid of poverty,

00:10:02.050 --> 00:10:03.240
get rid of discrimination.

00:10:03.240 --> 00:10:05.610
So, a more and more
expansionist view

00:10:05.610 --> 00:10:06.830
of what the State could do.

00:10:06.830 --> 00:10:11.320
But that vision, we think,
hits the buffers basically

00:10:11.320 --> 00:10:14.284
in the 1970s, because of
over expansion of the State.

00:10:14.284 --> 00:10:16.700
You get a reaction against
that under Reagan and Thatcher,

00:10:16.700 --> 00:10:19.350
who say we've got to
contract the State a bit.

00:10:19.350 --> 00:10:21.170
But that doesn't really work.

00:10:21.170 --> 00:10:22.320
They did important things.

00:10:22.320 --> 00:10:24.195
They got the state out
of running businesses,

00:10:24.195 --> 00:10:26.700
like British Rail,
British Leyland,

00:10:26.700 --> 00:10:29.840
which they shouldn't have been
running in the first place.

00:10:29.840 --> 00:10:33.087
They got the industrial
relations much more

00:10:33.087 --> 00:10:34.170
sorted out than they were.

00:10:34.170 --> 00:10:36.980
But the state
continues to expand.

00:10:36.980 --> 00:10:39.110
And what we're now
arguing, is that we're

00:10:39.110 --> 00:10:41.590
at the beginning of a
fourth revolution, driven

00:10:41.590 --> 00:10:44.260
by a number of forces, which
we'll talk about later.

00:10:44.260 --> 00:10:46.780
But essentially, which
gives us a chance

00:10:46.780 --> 00:10:50.320
to reinvent the State in
just as dramatic a way

00:10:50.320 --> 00:10:54.392
as it was reinvented in the 16th
century, in the 19th century,

00:10:54.392 --> 00:10:55.600
and then in the 20th century.

00:10:55.600 --> 00:10:57.000
And we need to do that.

00:10:59.185 --> 00:11:00.310
DON HARRISON: That's great.

